04739nam a22007095i 9780292793392DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212009txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927933927 a10.7560/7198422doi  a(DE-B1597)587161  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPS3511.E46bZ895 2010eb 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a813/.522221 aSmyth, J. E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEdna Ferber's Hollywood :bAmerican Fictions of Gender, Race, and History /cJ. E. Smyth. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2009  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tCHAPTER ONE Edna Ferber’s America and the Fictions of History -- tCHAPTER TWO The Life of an Unknown Woman: So Big, 1923–1953 -- tCHAPTER THREE Making Believe: Show Boat, Race, and Romance, 1925–1957 -- tCHAPTER FOUR Marking the Boundaries of Classical Hollywood’s Rise and Fall: Cimarron, 1928–1961 -- tCHAPTER FIVE Writing for Hollywood: Come and Get It and Saratoga Trunk, 1933–1947 -- tCHAPTER SIX Jim Crow, Jett Rink, and James Dean: Reconstructing Giant, 1952–1957 -- tCHAPTER SEVEN The New Nationalism: Ice Palace, 1954–1960 -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEdna Ferber's Hollywood reveals one of the most influential artistic relationships of the twentieth century—the four-decade partnership between historical novelist Edna Ferber and the Hollywood studios. Ferber was one of America's most controversial popular historians, a writer whose uniquely feminist, multiracial view of the national past deliberately clashed with traditional narratives of white masculine power. Hollywood paid premium sums to adapt her novels, creating some of the most memorable films of the studio era—among them Show Boat, Cimarron, and Giant. Her historical fiction resonated with Hollywood's interest in prestigious historical filmmaking aimed principally, but not exclusively, at female audiences. In Edna Ferber's Hollywood, J. E. Smyth explores the research, writing, marketing, reception, and production histories of Hollywood's Ferber franchise. Smyth tracks Ferber's working relationships with Samuel Goldwyn, Leland Hayward, George Stevens, and James Dean; her landmark contract negotiations with Warner Bros.; and the controversies surrounding Giant's critique of Jim-Crow Texas. But Edna Ferber's Hollywood is also the study of the historical vision of an American outsider—a woman, a Jew, a novelist with few literary pretensions, an unashamed middlebrow who challenged the prescribed boundaries among gender, race, history, and fiction. In a masterful film and literary history, Smyth explores how Ferber's work helped shape Hollywood's attitude toward the American past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aHistorical fiction, AmericanvFilm adaptations. 0aHistorical fiction, AmericanvTelevision adaptations. 0aHistorical fiction, AmericanxFilm adaptations. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRacism in literature. 0aSex role in literature. 0aWomen in the motion picture industryzUnited States. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aSchatz, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchatz, Thomas.40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/71984240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292793392423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292793392/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE